{"id":"d=origam-topic-4404//p=9d7c9304b9a740a39dc04b127f8e4cfb","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4404"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["8fadd9b162b14088bf2bc2ed9f13c06e"],"__file_part":["584a666da8564455b8df27e1e1769a6e"],"__part_n":["2"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4404"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-adjust-ux-ui-of-the-client-application/4404"],"title":["How to adjust UX/UI of the client application"],"imagesFound":["11"],"imagesDescribed":["11"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a388424a98f0d8b427f4923d6521d3f2a645bdd5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed5dca9cd0482563fce3dabab006bff3e46ec28e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b1b8d45cb8dff3797401bff08eb677f59c059a67.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/083f1cf3377ad4441cc8bdf267b814e121f275ee.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b6cbd4641981a6580362124f2208a5e042f2a3e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ffc5c8703e2f6dd56a18661ee9098cdbb64c11f7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/757f508ecacc20fc28a5bb41fbcb2bd2cb09e9d0.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40d3044d81054f4189021fce51d605019fa13edf.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0bc90246bb802c4f770ac7426df4e34c010ea9c5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/57b4ebb877107c4565dc52e95058ec6daebfef62.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8a565e0e2c67e7348fc83de8b7795515a49bf01a.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"activates the entire panel with record navigation, filtering, and other functions: \n   \n \n \n   Selection boxes to your workflow UI step screens \n You can provide any screen (section) with default system checkboxes that can be used in UI steps in sequential workflows for example. They don\u2019t serve for bulk actions like deleting of multiple selected items in the data grid view, they just set the  Selected  property in XML data to  true  or  false  which you can use in your transformations. \n To add the selection box do the following: \n \n Open the screen \n Click on the screen section \n Go to the  Properties  tab (accessible also from the main Menu under  View  or after pressing  F4 ) \n Find the  SelectionMember  property under  Misc  \n Enter the field name  Selected  \n Save it \n \n Now all lines in the grid view will contain a selection checkbox at the beginning: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ffc5c8703e2f6dd56a18661ee9098cdbb64c11f7.png]\nDescription: This image displays a task management interface, with a table containing tasks listed under two columns: \u0022Name\u0022 and \u0022Description.\u0022 The tasks include \u0022Add new users,\u0022 \u0022Insert all team tasks,\u0022 \u0022Prepare project kick-off,\u0022 \u0022Finalize the analysis,\u0022 and \u0022Pour plants.\u0022 Each task has a corresponding checkbox for selection. The descriptions provide specific actions related to each task. The interface likely serves the purpose of tracking and managing project-related tasks efficiently.\n\n\n  \n   Action buttons \n In addition to the main menu, there is another way to allow users to launch screens, workflows, and other elements: action buttons. \n These can be placed in the toolbar, the panel header, or the panel menu: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/757f508ecacc20fc28a5bb41fbcb2bd2cb09e9d0.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for managing tasks within an application. It features a top bar with options to \u0022Save,\u0022 \u0022Refresh,\u0022 and a search field. Below, under the \u0022Tasks\u0022 heading, there is a table with column headers \u0022Name\u0022 and \u0022Description.\u0022 The table contains a list of tasks, such as \u0022Insert all team tasks,\u0022 \u0022Get rid of all outdated paper documents,\u0022 \u0022Pour plants,\u0022 \u0022Prepare project kick-off,\u0022 and \u0022Finalize the analysis,\u0022 each accompanied by a corresponding description. Prominent buttons labeled \u0022Button 1\u0022 and \u0022Button 2\u0022 are visibly positioned, along with a dropdown menu accessible via \u0022Button 3,\u0022 offering options to \u0022Export to Excel,\u0022 \u0022Column Configuration,\u0022 and \u0022Show Record Information.\u0022 The visible pagination shows the user is currently viewing page 1 of 5. The overall purpose of this interface is to provide users with a structured way to manage and manipulate tasks.\n\n\n  \n   UI Actions \n Action buttons are created at the  Database Entity  level as  UI Actions . This means they are not defined via the target screen, workflow or else, but at the lowest possible level of the model \u2014 that is, at the database entity level. \n You can choose the following  action types : \n \n Menu Action \n Report Action \n Sequential Workflow Action \n Dropdown Action \n \n Here, we will demonstrate how to create a Sequential Workflow Action \u2014 an action button that triggers a selected workflow. \n To do this, select  New  /  Sequential Workflow Action  above your DB entity and fill in all required properties: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40d3044d81054f4189021fce51d605019fa13edf.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for configuring a Sequential Workflow Action named \u0022MyActionButton.\u0022 It is structured with multiple sections: an \u0022Info\u0022 section containing schema item details, including \u0022Name\u0022 and \u0022Inheritable\u0022 attributes; a \u0022Condition\u0022 section with settings under \u0022Keyboard\u0022 and \u0022Misc.\u0022 The \u0022Misc\u0022 category outlines parameters such as \u0022ActionType\u0022 (OpenForm), \u0022ButtonIcon,\u0022 and \u0022Caption\u0022 (My button). Additional properties include \u0022IsDefault,\u0022 \u0022ModalDialogHeight,\u0022 and \u0022Mode\u0022 (ActiveRecord), among others. The \u0022References\u0022 section lists \u0022ConfirmationMessage,\u0022 \u0022ConfirmationRule,\u0022 and a reference to \u0022Workflow\u0022 named \u0022MyWorkflow.\u0022 The overall purpose is to define the specifications and behaviors of a custom action in a workflow environment.\n\n\n  \n The following settings are also important here: \n \n  ActionType : Here are different options for what your action button can do \u2014 for example, open a form or run a workflow in the background. \n  IsModalDialog : Instead of a form will use modal dialog window. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:57:59"},"vector":[-0.012715751,-0.006471243,-0.09103405,0.04715914,0.014864817,-0.023458563,0.010350605,0.017675871,-0.010922055,0.006544779,-0.002741335,-0.036719088,0.006327611,0.04864543,0.054385275,0.0012717207,-0.010536846,0.023736289,0.034174647,0.009358341,-0.013842185,-0.011737252,0.025481641,0.04359396,-0.014047502,0.026017003,-0.0015996246,-0.041409537,-0.02941479,0.007660913,-0.008610903,-0.025638204,-0.015102894,-0.0072975266,-0.02787755,-0.003396565,-0.036457527,-0.022480786,-0.035978664,0.023501357,-0.022447657,0.011466019,-0.0068093333,-0.021738973,0.012206198,-0.046221923,0.01716807,-0.015465008,0.019352773,-0.055389207,-0.03961492,-0.027240835,0.016688848,-0.053399574,0.048518345,0.046659864,-0.05529981,-0.019143408,-0.060139462,0.0014589396,-0.0040025883,-0.0077753854,0.008205156,-0.0066970093,-0.015009914,-0.00611641,-0.022194885,0.0069856006,-0.018493606,-0.055084668,0.018123873,0.034125734,-0.041972466,-0.008742423,-0.027569525,0.0066178576,0.03237895,0.0072248676,0.012385848,0.010084765,-0.03435296,0.009358233,0.039425265,-0.017297557,0.